{
  "texts": [
    "Manufacturing defects refer to unintended flaws found in individual units of mass-produced items which deviate from the intended design.",
    "41 For manufacturing defects, U.S. law employs a standard close to strict liability (Wuyts, 2014, 10).",
    "A manufacturing defect occurs \"when an individual product (or batch) does not meet the standard of the general quality of its specific type even if all possible care was exercised.\"",
    "42 37 The test is objective in that it refers to the public's legitimate expectations, not the subjective expectations of the person who suffered harm, see Vansweevelt and Weyts (2009, 509).",
    "38 However, national courts have been using the risk-utility test to assess defects directly, for instance in France and the UK, see Wuyts (2014, 14-15), Borghetti et al. (2021)."
  ]
}